				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$T ( t )$\end{document}T(t) on the hospitalized infectious subpopulation. The slight and asymptomatic infectious do not need intensive treatment. Therefore the vaccination control is applied to the susceptible individuals, and the treatment control is applied to the hospitalized or seriously infectious individuals. Through the paper, we both formally and intuitively emphasize how those controls help to reduce the reproduction number. See, for instance, [29–31] and [36–38] and references therein for the motivation and use of the controls and the modeling issues for COVID-19, respectively. The SE(Is)(Ih)AR model to be discussed is the following one: 1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
